article.description:
Sheryl Swoopes scored 27 points, and Cynthia Cooper added 11 points and seven assists in her first game since
coming out of retirement as the Houston Comets beat the Seattle Storm 75-64 Thursday night.
article.headline: Cooper solid in return, Swoopes dazzling as always
article.linkText: Swoopes and Cooper reunited in Comets' opening win
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes scored 27 points, and Cynthia
Cooper added 11 points and seven assists in her first game since
coming out of retirement as the Houston Comets beat the Seattle
Storm 75-64 Thursday night.

	   Sue Bird had 19 points for the Storm, who pulled within six
points with 8:20 left before Houston pulled away with an 11-0 run.

	   Cooper helped the Comets win four straight WNBA titles before
retiring following the 2000 season. She won two MVP trophies and
three league scoring titles.

	   She got a rousing ovation when she ran onto the court for
pregame introductions. After committing a turnover in the opening
minute, she hit her first shot to give the Comets a 6-0 lead.

	   "I was a little nervous coming in. I didn't know how it would
turn out but Sheryl played an excellent game,'' Cooper said. "It
was a total team effort. We had two starters out but we came in and
played great basketball. I think after this game, I'll be able to
settle down and play basketball. I just needed to get this game out
of the way.''

	   The Storm shot terribly in the first half, hitting only one of
their first nine shots and three of their first 15 as the Comets
took a 14-7 lead with 12:07 to go.

	   Seattle cut the lead to 18-15 after seven straight points by Sue
Bird before Houston went on a 19-7 spurt. Cooper had nine of her 11
first-half points over the final 6:39.

	   After taking a 43-29 halftime lead, Houston hit only seven of 20
shots over the first nine minutes of the second half. The Storm
pulled within 62-56 with 8:20 on a 3-point basket by Bird.

	   The Comets put the game away with an 11-0 surge that started
with a 3-point basket by Ukari Figgs, followed by consecutive
baskets by Swoopes.

	   Janeth Arcain added 10 points for Houston. Lauren Jackson had 15
points and Adia Barnes and Sandy Brondello added 10 each for the
Storm.

	   While the Comets had the 40-year-old Cooper back, they played
the game without starter Tina Thompson and center Tiffani Johnson,
both sidelined with lower back injuries.

	   Houston's next game is against Phoenix, for whom Cooper coached.

	   "We're going to Phoenix and it's just another game but I want a
`W' because it's one more victory toward the championship,'' Cooper
said.
